Customer Segmentation - Case study

Objective: Create meaningful customer segments using the dataset and provide insights into the characteristics of each segment. For example:

  • Are certain clusters dominated by a gender?
  • What are the typical spending behaviours?
  • Are there any noticeable outliers?
  • What business decisions could be informed by these patterns?

EDA - Customer Demographics & Profile Analysis

  • Gender Distribution: 54.8% Male | 45.2% Female
  • Age Concentration: ~80% between ages 21-60 (core demographic)
  • Education: 62% Graduates | 38% Non-Graduates
  • Marital Status: 59% Ever-Married | 41% Never-Married

Gender & Life Stage Insights:

  • Marriage Patterns: Higher % of males ever-married vs. females never married
  • Age Distribution: Males dominate younger (0-20) and older (51-70) age groups
  • Education Gap: Among non-graduates, males significantly overrepresented

Professional Landscape:

  • Artist Heavy Economy: 31% of population are artists (largest profession)
  • Gender Segregation: Females concentrated in Engineering, Homemaker, Marketing; Males in Entertainment, Executive, Healthcare
  • Experience Distribution: 62% have 0-1 years work experience (early career dominant ??)

Family Structure:

  • 90% have family sizes 1 - 4
  • Single Person Households: Only family size 1 shows female majority
  • Career Marriage Correlation: <4% under-30s married; <8% over-40s never married

Young, creative population with early career (work exp < 2) suggests growth stage market with high engagement potential but developing spending power

Spending Pattern Analysis

  • Low Spenders: 60% of population (dominant segment)

  • Average Spenders: 24% of population

  • High Spenders: 14% of population (premium opportunity)

  • Gender & Spending Dynamics:

    • Males have higher % composition in Average and High spending groups

  • Age-Based Spending Insights:

    • Young Budget Conscious: 45% of low spenders are under 40 years
    • Mature Premium Segment: High spenders consistently 15-20% across 41+ age groups
    • Average spenders concentrate 80% in 31-60 age range

  • Professional Spending Behaviors:

    • Premium Professions: Lawyers (52% high spenders) and Executives (65% high spenders)
    • Budget-Constrained Sectors: Healthcare (93% low spenders), Marketing (82% low spenders)
    • Balanced Spenders: Artists, Engineers, Entertainment show average spending patterns

  • Marriage & Spending Correlation:

    • Single Budget Focus: 41% of population = never-married low spenders
    • Family Financial Responsibility: 24% = married average spenders
    • Premium Family Segment: 19% = married low spenders (value-conscious families)

60% low-spending base - upselling opportunity ??; 14% premium segment - high value customers

Segmentation Methodology

Feature engineering

  • Profession Categorization: Grouped careers into skill tiers (High-Skill: Doctor/Engineer/Executive vs Creative vs Service/Care) based on market value and requirements
  • Life Stage Classification: Combined age, marital status, and work experience into meaningful life phases - Career Starter, Young Professional, Established Adult, Senior Segment, Transitional
  • Economic Capacity Index: Weighted scoring system (0-100) integrating profession tier (40%), education level (30%), and spending behavior (30%) to capture purchasing power
  • Family Responsibility Factor: Age-adjusted multiplier accounting for marital status and family size to understand financial obligations and decision-making complexity
  • Profession - Education match: boolean variable indicating comparison of job typ and education level (eg: High-Skill and Graduate/Non-Graduate)

Data preprocesisng pipeline

  • Categorical Encoding: OneHotEncoder applied to categorical variables
  • Numerical Standardization: StandardScaler used to normalize numerical variable
  • Dimensionality Reduction: PCA implemented to capture 95% variance while reducing noise

Ensemble approach - Multi Algorithm Consensus Clustering

STAGE 1: Algorithm Ensemble

  • HDBSCAN Density-based natural clusters
  • K-Means Centroid-based balanced groups
  • Hierarchical Tree-based relationship mapping

STAGE 2: Consensus Identification

  • Cross-algorithm validation
  • 76% stable consensus data identified (customers falling into same across the 3 algorithms, and size of cluster >4% )
  • 24% edge cases separated for specialized analysis

STAGE 3: Refined Segmentation

  • Core segments: 4 stable clusters (high confidence)
  • Niche segments: 4 specialized micro-clusters

Validation Framework

  • Cluster profiles across features
  • Gap Statistic + Silhouette Analysis for optimal cluster count
  • t-SNE visualization confirming clear separation
  • Ensure cluster stability through consensus identification

tSNE representation of clusters

Cluster profiles

  • Cluster 1: 'Senior Business High Spenders Married Educated Males Small Families Early Career' (1219 customers, 14.6%)

    • Successful business leaders in their 50s+, married with small families. High spenders - Quality first, price second.

  • Cluster 2: 'Young Professionals Budget Conscious Single Non-Graduates Males Medium Families Early Career' (1519 customers, 18.2%)

    • Young guys in their 20s-30s, single, building their careers, supporting medium-sized families. Values buyers, price consious; probably Future high value customers.

  • Cluster 3: 'Mid Age Business Budget Conscious Married Educated Females Small Families Early Career' (1514 customers, 18.1%)

    • Mid-career professional women balancing work and family life, value focused with family needs in mind. Family-friendly products and services that solve real problems ?

  • Cluster 4: 'Mid Age Creatives Budget Conscious Married Educated Males Small Families Early Career' (2127 customers, 25.4%)

    • Largest Segment - Mid-career creative types, married, educated, but watching their budgets. Would value authenticity over flashy marketing.

  • Cluster 5: 'Senior Creatives Budget Conscious Married Non-Graduates Males Small Families Early Career' (336 customers, 4.0%)

    • Niche but loyal - Older creative professionals, budget conscious. Word of mouth driven, would prefers established brands.

  • Cluster 6: 'Mid Age Professionals Budget Conscious Married Educated Males Small Families Early Career' (281 customers, 3.4%)

    • Mid-career professionals (lawyers, consultants), married, budget-minded

  • Cluster 7: 'Mid Age Creatives Budget Conscious Married Non-Graduates Males Small Families Early Career' (604 customers, 7.2%)

    • Mid-career creatives without formal education, married. Would value simplicity and durability

  • Cluster 8: 'Mid Age Creatives Average Spenders Married Educated Males Small Families Mid Career' (763 customers, 9.1%)

    • Established creative professionals, might be willing to spend on quality
